uestions about the service file structure.\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_bhyYP9OgIV1UNqHL6NASoIpR|fc_0a92bb1da5926a480169f0e8540f7481939d5709efa147ec89\", \"name\": \"bash\", \"arguments\": {\"command\": \"rg -n \\\"-processor|XprintProcessorInfo|ServiceLoader|ANNOTATION_PROCESSOR_PATH|setProcessors\\\" local_repositories/source_context/org.eclipse.jdt/ecj/3.26.0/main/extracted tests/src/org.eclipse.jdt/ecj/3.26.0/src/test/java -S\", \"timeout\": 10}}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 775, \"output\": 1316, \"cacheRead\": 14336, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 16427, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"total\": 0}}, \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\", \"timestamp\": 1777395775183, \"responseId\": \"resp_0a92bb1da5926a480169f0e83f923c8193966c608aa9c44768\"}}\nhuman-intervention-logs/org.eclipse.jdt:ecj:3.26.0/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-04-28T17-05-57-068355Z.log:1213:[tool-exec] start id=call_bhyYP9OgIV1UNqHL6NASoIpR|fc_0a92bb1da5926a480169f0e8540f7481939d5709efa147ec89 name=bash args={\"command\": \"rg -n \\\"-processor|XprintProcessorInfo|ServiceLoader|ANNOTATION_PROCESSOR_PATH|setProcessors\\\" local_repositories/source_context/org.eclipse.jdt/ecj/3.26.0/main/extracted tests/src/org.eclipse.jdt/ecj/3.26.0/src/test/java -S\", \"timeout\": 10}\nhuman-intervention-logs/org.eclipse.jdt:ecj:3.26.0/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-04-28T17-05-57-068355Z.log:1221:[recv] {\"type\": \"turn_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Evaluating service loader test**\\n\\nI'm considering how to handle the service loader test. Instead of using `-processor`, I could set `-processorpath` to a temporary processor jar or output classes. But there's a concern that the dynamic ClassLoader might not work with native images. Currently, I'm utilizing EclipseCompiler to compile fixtures and directly set the processor, which avoids the need for discovery. However, I’m thinking about creating source files for the processor and compiling them, which poses challenges in native images since `javac` might not be available. So, I may need to rely on the test's own processor class instead.\\n\\n**Evaluating Java test structure**\\n\\nI'm thinking about the one-to-one mapping and whether \\\"keeping coverage for the active class in its own dedicated Java test file\\\" really means no auxiliary files should be necessary. Maybe having a nested public static class is acceptable if the service provider supports it. I wonder if the ServiceLoader provider class can also be nested as public static? It seems to load binary names with $, which raises some questions about the service file structure.\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_0a92bb1da5926a480169f0e8412c48819396b25ee834bc157d\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABp8OhURndeqhdEqL1k19HmtKnTIUzvsrZ-8SqPmQaj64pWvDSctyKmRSlnVjmBy8hZbRO82Eke_aygZ19VV2EP7Yx6HuNEI7Q83bOG3LF4EzCeyvufsne5J47NTcTPI9zUfAGnlzqqJHzeD1CCiJHOmS3uV1IrCYLAC9kunsov6pG0WfitHwXmxRsybjU5rvVWHPeEMtzD4MakufFCuDa8T-lXASl9P722mSGP3wMqoO7VJR7kDhey_CTwrO6QQ1wx1BHBThpyPPeshEb_8-V4PMiDlDDGmQQzJckHeTdB-8RhDwXohtbJiizAFoN3t_xv_Uiun2fHb_yUfPI8t8OuKeDtCUfFrH7vGevdX4MSy52AC2fxcQKFFwEHTnGwmHeneFAcexQMyviwEljKBhXD5kOT6G4zsnsa9s8mTYPAjF4zda3aneCu4g_xa9wfmlfCWOpTTJ2rztYZFeIYGvQyFugaBzErpsmuCuat1flu4h8HWzCZhYSUMrkxQJlHqtUdhiWCenbpHj7LJRUtHs8sniP_IIuLMIDuB145V9UuMq6T-qvovQBkmdMaCR936SOa6rhpZ7T-l9w8WuP-5ETUOmEXEZ8CCQ82JBfcVPeqztxKATbevLsfz0JFXJrwckZd5FleRZa79MSzeVfX2nEYW9xe_8TexwJGVUS9-m9jIkZ8YCgv-0cMVdEpEFLbQJHo5ShAQhGx-juzy_k4dkzmr8F8Ixb4LOf6jZ1wtCAggYUBgk2GqcD-Dae1JyTJByiT7JJYKq0ty8-ydVNnzaYWTuNhYw4ay5cY3Ytkocm4DKT8qFROq4joSpXTgTAHMpo4-j6OD3jSdQjY5-ZFIwgOjkhvgJZ9R90w4JTOhJgOAmNbg1rqElYitMbaq0dmo9RMtWXkUrTKGiSp0PS9Xxn2nLRfGb22kYG4mKLiNxmYnSNjIdn3_5c06HhO8Wl6r5sezkXw43Z9jrXYAKAI732M-PTiL_lSEqacXy_w4hb-0Fksoq